INSERT INTO `revision` (`page_id`,`rev_id`,`text`,`user_id`,`user_text`,`major`,`created`,`tags`,`deleted`) VALUES (59,1,'ì˜¹ê³¨ ì§‘í•©\r\n\r\n== Definition ==\r\nA subset K of a [[Topology|topological space]] X is called compact set if every open cover of K contains a finite subcover.\r\n\r\n== Criterion ==\r\n * In Euclidean space, closed and bounded set is compact.\r\n\r\n== Properties ==\r\n=== General ===\r\n * Compactness is a property of the set it self in some way, which means: $X \\subset Y$, Y is a topological space, X is topological subspace of Y. Then if K is compact relative to X, also relative to Y, vice versa.\r\n * Closed subset of a compact set is compact.\r\n * Infinite subset of K has a limit point in K.\r\n\r\n=== In [[metric space]] X ===\r\n * Compact set is closed.((This is not true in general case. Consider $(X, T)$ where $X = \\{a, b\\}, T = \\{\\emptyset, \\{a\\}, \\{a, b\\}\\}$))\r\n * Intersection of a closed set with K is also compact.\r\n *  If $ \\{ K_\\alpha\\} $ is a collection of compact subsets of a metric space X such that the intersection of every finite subcollection is nonempty, then $\\cap K_\\alpha \\neq \\emptyset$\r\n * K is compact $\\Leftrightarrow$ Every infinite subset of K has a limit point in E.\r\n * A sequence in K has a subsequence that converges in X.\r\n\r\n{{cat ìˆ˜í•™}}\r\n{{cat Analysis}}\r\n{{cat Topology}}',1,'::ffff:192.168.35.1',0,'2017-06-08 15:38:57.000',NULL,0);
